5000|$|Shrimsley wrote three novels {{after his}} retirement: The Candidates, Lion Rampant and The <b>Silly</b> <b>Season</b> (2003). The <b>Silly</b> <b>Season,</b> wrote Roy Greenslade in The Guardian, is a [...] "fine piece of satire" [...] about tabloid journalism which {{contains}} [...] "considerable wit and verve". It contains [...] "a thinly veiled portrait" [...] of former Sun editor, Kelvin MacKenzie, combined with {{elements of the}} [...] "self-publicising egoism" [...] of Piers Morgan, then editor of the Mirror.|$|E
